    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Feature description\n\nIn Vim script there are the two variables `v:exception` and `v:throwpoint`, but they only work in pure Vim script. If the exception is handled in Lua through `pcall` we can get the error message through the second return value, but not the location because neither `vim.v.exception` nor `vim.v.throwpoint` are set.\r\n\r\nFurthermore passing a second parameter (`level`) to `error` in Lua should control the depth of the stack trace contained in the error message, and a `level` of `0` should supress the stack trace entirely ([source](https://www.lua.org/manual/5.1/manual.html#pdf-error)). But it doesn't look like the `level` has any effect on the error message, which makes it impossible to get short messages like we get them from `throw` in Vim script.\r\n\r\nI think `vim.v.exception` and `vim.v.throwpoint` should work in Lua as well. Error messages without stack trace can be useful if the user really wants terse messages which will be handled.",
